<br>
  As I understand from reading multiple sources, there was a free speech zone setup specifically for the event a good distance away, and this guy decided he didn't want to protest there he wanted to get right up there.<br>
<br>
  At that point he refused a request by the security personnel to relocate his protest, informing them of his right to free assembly and was arrested.  Mind you unlike that article, numerous articles pointed out that he was the lone protester among various participants.  (The rest of the protestors were apparently at the designated zone)<br>
<br>
  I guess you have to ask yourself, where do you draw the line.  American's have the right to free assembly, but does that mean that you can go walking up on the white house lawn and sit down with a picket sign?  After all you are peaceably assembling on public property.<br>
<br>
  Currently if you want to protest, you have to get a permit as I understand and are designated an area that you can protest in, and if you exceed the limitations of that area, then you are in violation of the law.<br>
<br>
  Basically what the guy was pissed about is the setup spot was too far away from the actual address for him to be heard.  I'm sorry but Boo-fucking-hoo.  You are there to protest, not to drown out someone's speech.  You get enough people there and I assure you the camera's will take notice of you no matter where you are standing. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=204898">Ayiar Frullaniaceae</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
